{"parentUuid":"d48682be-031a-4ec7-b3e8-e712e2bcca64","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b6d534eb-f80d-405a-a05d-4c7eb6280654","agentId":"aff0c9553677dd11a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LtacbJqiyjhSFwn855A1YX","type":"tool_result","content":"1:# Requirements — quota administration (list + delete)\n4:- How does DELETE /v1/quotas identify the quota? → Query parameters: `DELETE /v1/quotas?customer_id=X&metric=Y`. No request body. The params are validated against the exact same anchored allowlists PUT uses (`CustomerId`, `Metric` in `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`).\n5:- What does DELETE return when no quota exists for that (customer_id, metric) in the caller's tenant? → 404 with the API's standard error envelope — deletes are explicit, not silently idempotent.\n6:- What does DELETE return on success? → 204 No Content, no body.\n9:- Who may call GET /v1/quotas? → Admin scope only, same as PUT and DELETE — all of `/v1/quotas` reuses the existing `_require_admin_and_throttled` gate (auth → Tier-2 throttle → admin-scope check).\n10:- Tenancy → Both endpoints operate strictly within the authenticated principal's own tenant (`api_key_id`), exactly like PUT; no cross-tenant read or delete is possible.\n11:- DELETE racing an in-flight POST /v1/events → Acceptable. No special synchronization: requests that read the quota before the delete commits may still be rejected against the old cap; enforcement stops for all requests that read after commit. Matches existing PUT-replacement semantics.\n12:- Non-functional / data / observability defaults confirmed → No new perf budget beyond the API's existing p95 targets; quota rows are non-sensitive operational config (no new data-protection class); deletes are logged through the existing structured-logging conventions.\n19:- Pagination or filtering on GET /v1/quotas.\n23:- Resetting or touching recorded usage when a quota is deleted — deletion removes the cap only."}]},"uuid":"cc5ef36e-a77e-426a-99a3-9